rounds.response:
After accepting the last trade I lost  
5 Brick (my best non-Ore value) and 5 Sheep, but gained 10 Wheat and 5 Wood.  
Let me check whether the deal left me with any clear surplus at the margin:

• Brick is now 17 @20 = 340  
• Sheep is now 14 @17 = 238  
• Wheat rises to 25 @6 = 150  
• Wood rises to 27 @9 = 243  

In total I gained 393 value while giving up 400 value, so the previous trade was break-even at best.  
To turn the corner and increase my total value, I want to convert some of the low-value Wheat and Wood into higher-value Brick and especially Ore.  

Player 0 gave me 10 Wheat (and some Wood), so I know he now wants/needs Brick and Sheep.  
He also gave up on making a new offer, which suggests he might sit on his gain for a while.  

I will therefore propose a symmetrical counter-offer this turn that flips the proportion while keeping the same items visible.

[Offer: 10 Wheat, 5 Wood -> 5 Brick, 5 Ore]
